main event: A funnel-shaped white object, the size of a grapefruit, was observed for 2 hours and 50 minutes over South Weymouth, Massachusetts on November 10, 1956.
interesting points: The object appeared to be at an elevation of 100 degrees azimuth and disappeared at an elevation of 170 degrees azimuth.
The object was initially spotted at 15 degrees elevation and 100 degrees azimuth, then drifted from east to south between 2,000 to 12,000 feet in altitude.
The object passed through the coast at an altitude of 12,000 feet.
The sighting was made by two civilian guards on duty, and the object was also tracked by Fourth Cliff radar research site in Humarock, Massachusetts.
The report states that there was no known air traffic in the area at the time of the sighting, and a preliminary analysis could not determine the cause of the sighting.
